         <div>
            <entry xml:id="L90381d433e9e446491efa12927baa76c" n="12674">
               <form><foreign xml:lang="gez">ተንበለ</foreign></form>
               <sense xml:id="Tmain" xml:lang="en" source="#traces">
                  <cit type="transcription" xml:lang="gez">
                     <quote>tanbala</quote>
                  </cit> I, 1 <foreign xml:lang="gez">ወምስለ፡ ዝኵሉ፡ ኢያፀርዕ፡ ሐቲተ፡ መጻሕፍት፡ ቅዱሳን፡ እስከ፡ ተንበለ፡
                     በአእምሮቶን፡ እምአዕሩግ፡ መንፈሳዊያን።</foreign> ‘<cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>Despite this, he did not cease to explore the holy books (scriptures)
                        until he became capable in understanding them, more than the spiritual
                        elders</quote>
                  </cit>’ <bibl><ptr target="bm:Solomon2019GalawdewosI"/><citedRange unit="page"> 63
                        § 121 (ed.)</citedRange></bibl>, <bibl><ptr target="bm:Solomon2019GalawdewosII"/><citedRange unit="page"> 37 § 121
                        (tr.)</citedRange></bibl> (‘The word <foreign xml:lang="gez">ተንበለ</foreign>
                  originates from the Arabic word <foreign xml:lang="ar">تنبّ</foreign> {tanabbala}
                  which means ‘be clever and capable’. Cf. <bibl><ptr target="bm:Conzelman1895Galawdewos"/><citedRange unit="page">
                        156</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="bm:Pereira1900Susenyos"/><citedRange unit="page"> 304</citedRange></bibl>.’) <bibl><ptr target="bm:Solomon2019GalawdewosII"/><citedRange unit="page"> 37 n.
                        186</citedRange></bibl>
                  <nd/>
               </sense>
            </entry>
         </div>
